// Canonical Sutra declarations for the transcendental-function
// family (log / sqrt / exp / sin / cos / tan / pow).
//
// **Status (2026-04-30): NOT IMPLEMENTED. Compile-time error if used.**
//
// History:
//   - 2026-04-25: Intrinsic declarations landed as placeholders;
//     runtime stubs raised NotImplementedError.
//   - 2026-04-29: A Taylor + frexp + Newton-refinement implementation
//     was wired in commit e45d373. Math returned correct values, but
//     the implementation ran as host Python scalar arithmetic (Python
//     `for n in range(25): acc = 1.0 + r * acc / n` over Python floats),
//     not as substrate tensor ops on CUDA. The commit message claimed
//     "substrate-pure" but the architecture was wrong.
//   - 2026-04-30: Implementation withdrawn. The codegen now rejects
//     calls to any of the seven names with CodegenNotSupported. The
//     intrinsic declarations remain so the parser knows the names exist;
//     the compile-time error fires from `_translate_call` in
//     `codegen_base.py` (`_TRANSCENDENTALS_DISABLED` set).
//
// Documentation of what was tried and what failed:
//   - chats/implementing-transcendental-functions.md — the original
//     design conversation (bound-table-via-binding, eigenrotation
//     hopes, etc.).
//   - planning/findings/2026-04-29-bound-table-capacity-limit.md —
//     why the bound-table architecture doesn't work for non-periodic
//     functions (Gibbs phenomenon, 2-scalar bundle capacity).
//   - planning/findings/2026-04-30-runtime-substrate-purity-audit.md
//     — why the Taylor-on-Python-floats implementation was withdrawn.
//
// **Future direction: eigenrotation-as-modulus** (Emma 2026-04-30).
// The unit-circle rotation is naturally periodic — applying R(θ)
// arbitrarily many times wraps around the circle without needing
// floor-based range reduction. This might be a path to substrate-pure
// trig (and by extension exp/log via complex composition) that doesn't
// hit the bound-table capacity wall. Hunch only, not a design yet.
// Actual design and implementation belongs in `planning/open-questions/`
// when someone picks it up.
//
// **Why disabled rather than fixed**: the transcendentals are a
// "look at this cool thing our language can do" feature, not
// fundamental runtime. The fundamental runtime is the RNN substrate
// (loop bodies, binding, bundling, etc.). Disabling the broken
// transcendentals frees focus for getting the fundamental pieces right
// without leaving an architectural lie behind that could mislead
// downstream users into thinking their `exp(x)` runs on CUDA when it
// actually runs in CPython.
//
// TODO: re-implement via eigenrotation-as-modulus when the design
// is drafted. Expected entry point: a new section here describing the
// substrate-pure architecture, with the codegen guard removed once
// the implementation is verified to actually run as tensor ops.


// ==========================================================================
// Intrinsic declarations — class-as-namespace form
// ==========================================================================
//
// These names exist for the parser so that referenced calls have a
// known symbol. The codegen (`codegen_base.py::_translate_call` in
// the `_TRANSCENDENTALS_DISABLED` branch) rejects them with a clear
// CodegenNotSupported error pointing at this file.
//
// Migrated 2026-05-01 from top-level `intrinsic function` declarations
// to the class-as-namespace shape per the encapsulation taxonomy. The
// stdlib_loader registers each entry under both the bare name (`log`)
// and the namespaced name (`Math.log`), so existing user code that
// calls `log(x)` still resolves and the new `Math.log(x)` shape is
// also recognized.

class Math extends vector {
    static intrinsic method scalar log(scalar x);
    static intrinsic method scalar sqrt(scalar x);
    static intrinsic method scalar exp(scalar x);
    static intrinsic method scalar sin(scalar x);
    static intrinsic method scalar cos(scalar x);
    static intrinsic method scalar tan(scalar x);
    static intrinsic method scalar pow(scalar x, scalar y);
}
